  abstract = {{$<$}section class="abstract"{$><$}h2 class="abstractTitle text-title my-1" id="d57751893e101"{$>$}Abstract{$<$}/h2{$><$}p{$>$}This paper examines the role of wave\textendash mean flow interaction in the onset and suddenness of stratospheric sudden warmings (SSWs). Evidence is presented that SSWs are, on average, a threshold behavior of finite-amplitude Rossby waves arising from the competition between an increasing wave activity {$<$}em{$>$}A{$<$}/em{$>$} and a decreasing zonal-mean zonal wind {$<$}inline-formula xmlns:ifp="http://www.ifactory.com/press" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/"{$><$}math{$><$}mrow{$><$}mover accent="true"{$><$}mi{$>$}u{$<$}/mi{$><$}mo{$>$}\textasciimacron{$<$}/mo{$><$}/mover{$><$}/mrow{$><$}/math{$><$}/inline-formula{$>$}. The competition puts a limit to the wave activity flux that a stationary Rossby wave can transmit upward. A rapid, spontaneous vortex breakdown occurs once the upwelling wave activity flux reaches the limit, or equivalently, once {$<$}inline-formula xmlns:ifp="http://www.ifactory.com/press" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/"{$><$}math{$><$}mrow{$><$}mover accent="true"{$><$}mi{$>$}u{$<$}/mi{$><$}mo{$>$}\textasciimacron{$<$}/mo{$><$}/mover{$><$}/mrow{$><$}/math{$><$}/inline-formula{$>$} drops below a certain fraction of {$<$}em{$>$}u{$<$}/em{$>$}\textsubscript{REF}, a wave-free, reference-state wind inverted from the zonalized quasigeostrophic potential vorticity. This fraction is 0.5 in theory and about 0.3 in reanalyses. We propose {$<$}inline-formula xmlns:ifp="http://www.ifactory.com/press" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/"{$><$}math{$><$}mrow{$><$}mi{$>$}r{$<$}/mi{$><$}mo{$>\equiv<$}/mo{$><$}mrow{$><$}mrow{$><$}mover accent="true"{$><$}mi{$>$}u{$<$}/mi{$><$}mo{$>$}\textasciimacron{$<$}/mo{$><$}/mover{$><$}/mrow{$><$}mo{$>$}/{$<$}/mo{$><$}mrow{$><$}msub{$><$}mi{$>$}u{$<$}/mi{$><$}mrow{$><$}mtext{$>$}REF{$<$}/mtext{$><$}/mrow{$><$}/msub{$><$}/mrow{$><$}/mrow{$><$}/mrow{$><$}/