tion is present without Arctic CO2 forcing in all seasons but summer, independent of where the forcing is applied south of 60\textdegree{} N. South of the forcing area, both in the Arctic and northern mid-latitude forcing simulations, the warming is generally limited to less than 0.5~\textdegree C. In contrast, north of the forcing area in the northern mid-latitude forcing experiments, the warming amounts to generally more than 1~\textdegree C close to the surface, except for summer. This is a strong indication that the influence of warming outside of the Arctic on the Arctic is substantial, while forcing applied only in the Arctic mainly materializes in a warming Arctic, with relatively small implications for non-Arctic regions.},
